const h="03",n={en:"Research Gaps in the Study of Christianity in Vietnam",vi:"Khoảng trống nghiên cứu trong việc nghiên cứu Kitô giáo tại Việt Nam"},i={en:"Christianity has been present in Vietnam for nearly five centuries, yet the scholarly literature remains remarkably uneven. Catholic missionary history from the Jesuit period onward is reasonably well documented, but vast stretches of time, geography, ethnicity, and theological inquiry remain underexplored. This report catalogs approximately 30 understudied areas organized into seven categories --- chronological, geographic, denominational, ethnic, thematic, diaspora, and comparative --- and explains what is missing, why it matters, and what kind of research would begin to fill each gap.",vi:"Kitô giáo đã hiện diện tại Việt Nam gần năm thế kỷ, nhưng tài liệu học thuật vẫn không đồng đều đáng kể. Lịch sử truyền giáo Công giáo được ghi chép khá tốt, nhưng nhiều khoảng thời gian, địa lý, sắc tộc và thần học vẫn chưa được khám phá. Báo cáo này liệt kê khoảng 30 lĩnh vực chưa được nghiên cứu đầy đủ, tổ chức theo bảy loại --- niên đại, địa lý, giáo phái, sắc tộc, chủ đề, hải ngoại và so sánh. [Bản dịch AI — Chờ xem xét]"},e=["gaps","scholarship","contemporary"],t=16,a=!1,o=JSON.parse(`[{"heading":{"en":"Chronological Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống theo niên đại"},"content":{"en":"### Pre-Jesuit Contact Period (1533--1615)\\n\\nBetween fragmentary mentions of early Portuguese contact and the Jesuit arrival in 1615, almost nothing has been published. **What is needed:** Archival research in Lisbon, Goa, and Macau; analysis of Vietnamese imperial records; archaeological investigation of early Portuguese trading posts.\\n\\n### Tay Son Period Christianity (1770s--1800s)\\n\\nThe Tay Son rebellion and dynasty represents massive political upheaval during which missionary activity continued but is poorly documented. **What is needed:** Vietnamese-language archival research; translation of French missionary correspondence.\\n\\n### Japanese Occupation Era (1940--1945)\\n\\nHow Christian institutions navigated dual colonial authority (French Vichy and Japanese military control) is largely undocumented. **What is needed:** Oral history (urgent, as last witnesses are dying); Japanese military archives; Vatican diplomatic correspondence.\\n\\n### Immediate Post-Reunification Underground Church (1975--1986)\\n\\nThe decade between reunification and Doi Moi is documented almost entirely from exile accounts, not systematic scholarship. By war's end there were roughly 154,000 Evangelical Christians, many in underground churches. Vietnamese pastors smuggled Hmong-language Bibles and ran underground Bible schools. **What is needed:** Oral history projects; declassified government surveillance records; denominational archive analysis.","vi":"### Giai đoạn trước Dòng Tên (1533--1615)\\n\\nHầu như không có tài liệu được xuất bản. Cần nghiên cứu lưu trữ tại Lisbon, Goa và Ma Cao.\\n\\n### Thời kỳ Tây Sơn (1770s--1800s)\\n\\nHoạt động truyền giáo tiếp tục nhưng thiếu tài liệu.\\n\\n### Thời kỳ Nhật chiếm đóng (1940--1945)\\n\\nCác tổ chức Kitô giáo đối phó với quyền lực kép như thế nào chưa được ghi nhận.\\n\\n### Giáo hội bí mật sau thống nhất (1975--1986)\\n\\nGiai đoạn này chủ yếu được ghi nhận từ tài liệu lưu vong."}},{"heading":{"en":"Geographic Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống theo địa lý"},"content":{"en":"### Central Highlands Christianity Among Ethnic Minorities\\n\\nA distinctive form called *Tin Lanh Dega* (\\"Dega Protestantism\\") blends cultural pride, political autonomy, and evangelism. The Vietnamese government banned it as separatist. Human Rights Watch has documented forced renunciations and imprisonment. Academic scholarship on the religious dimensions remains thin. **What is needed:** Ethnographic fieldwork; theological analysis; comparative study.\\n\\n### Northern Vietnam Protestant Growth Post-2000\\n\\nThe most dramatic church growth since 2000 has occurred in northern provinces among Hmong, driven by radio evangelism, not foreign missionaries, under tighter government surveillance. **What is needed:** Quantitative mapping of church planting; institutional analysis; comparison of northern/southern Protestant ecclesiology.\\n\\n### Mekong Delta Catholic Communities\\n\\nSome of Vietnam's oldest Catholic parishes alongside newer communities formed after 1954. The delta's unique ecology and ethnic diversity shape church life in understudied ways.\\n\\n### Urban vs. Rural Church Dynamics\\n\\nVietnam's rapid urbanization is reshaping Christianity, but the literature treats \\"the Vietnamese church\\" as monolithic. Ho Chi Minh City megachurch-adjacent congregations, Hanoi's small registered churches, and rural house churches represent fundamentally different realities.","vi":"### Tây Nguyên\\n\\n*Tin Lành Dega* bị chính phủ cấm vì coi là ly khai. Cần nghiên cứu dân tộc học và thần học.\\n\\n### Miền Bắc Việt Nam sau 2000\\n\\nTăng trưởng mạnh nhất qua truyền giáo radio trong cộng đồng Hmong.\\n\\n### Đồng bằng sông Cửu Long và thành thị vs nông thôn\\n\\nCác cộng đồng Công giáo lâu đời và sự khác biệt giữa giáo hội thành thị và nông thôn chưa được nghiên cứu."}},{"heading":{"en":"Denominational and Tradition Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống theo giáo phái và truyền thống"},"content":{"en":"### Protestant House Church Movement\\n\\nBy the early 2000s, more than half of Vietnamese Protestants belonged to evangelical house churches rather than registered denominations. In 1988, a house church movement began when pastors were expelled from official churches; leader Tran Dinh Ai built a network reaching 16,000 members and 165 churches by 1997. Systematic academic study barely exists.\\n\\n### Pentecostal and Charismatic Growth\\n\\nAbout one-third to one-half of Vietnamese evangelicals identify with Pentecostalism. Ethnic minorities make up 14% of Vietnam's population yet account for three-quarters of all evangelicals. Vince Le's *Vietnamese Evangelicals and Pentecostalism* (2019) is a landmark but the field needs far more work.\\n\\n### Smaller Denominations\\n\\nSeventh-day Adventists (founded in Saigon 1929, ~16,000 members in 2025), Baptist Convention (509 churches, 51,000 members in 2023), Mennonites, Methodists, and Church of Christ have virtually no dedicated scholarship.\\n\\n### Indigenous Vietnamese Christian Movements\\n\\nDistinctly Vietnamese Christian movements initiated without foreign denominational affiliation are poorly documented.","vi":"### Phong trào nhà thờ gia đình\\n\\nHơn một nửa người Tin Lành thuộc nhà thờ gia đình, nhưng hầu như không có nghiên cứu học thuật.\\n\\n### Các giáo phái nhỏ\\n\\nCác nhóm như Adventist, Baptist, Mennonite chưa có nghiên cứu chuyên biệt."}},{"heading":{"en":"Ethnic and Demographic Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống về sắc tộc và nhân khẩu học"},"content":{"en":"### Hmong Christianity\\n\\nPerhaps the most consequential gap. Roughly one-third of Vietnam's 1.4 million Hmong have converted to Protestantism in just thirty years, beginning when villagers encountered Hmong-language radio broadcasts from Manila --- with no foreign missionaries physically present. The northern mountainous region now has 300,000 Hmong Protestants. Toan Thanh Nguyen's *The New Way* (2021) has begun to address this, but the scale of the phenomenon far outpaces the scholarship.\\n\\n### Montagnard/Degar Christian Communities\\n\\nBeyond human rights documentation, the internal religious life --- theology, leadership formation, worship practices --- is barely studied.\\n\\n### Khmer Krom and Christianity\\n\\nThe Khmer Krom are overwhelmingly Theravada Buddhist, but small Christian communities exist among them. The intersection of ethnic identity, Buddhist heritage, and Christian conversion is entirely unstudied.\\n\\n### Youth and Generational Shifts\\n\\nVietnamese Americans account for 4% of newly ordained Catholic priests and 8% of all seminarians nationwide. Yet market economy pressures and secularization are creating generational fault lines. Church leaders report materialism is drawing young Catholics away from faith.","vi":"### Kitô giáo Hmong\\n\\nKhoảng một phần ba trong 1,4 triệu người Hmong đã cải đạo chỉ trong 30 năm, qua đài phát thanh không có nhà truyền giáo nước ngoài.\\n\\n### Cộng đồng Montagnard/Dega\\n\\nĐời sống tôn giáo nội bộ hầu như chưa được nghiên cứu.\\n\\n### Thanh niên và chuyển đổi thế hệ\\n\\nÁp lực kinh tế thị trường và thế tục hóa đang tạo ra những đứt gãy thế hệ."}},{"heading":{"en":"Thematic Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống theo chủ đề"},"content":{"en":"### Vietnamese Theology\\n\\nWhat does an indigenous Vietnamese Christian theology look like? KimSon Nguyen has proposed frameworks including God as Dao (the Way) and ancestor veneration as theological framework. But these remain isolated proposals, not a sustained tradition. The core challenge: presenting Christian faith so that Vietnamese can follow Christ while remaining culturally Vietnamese.\\n\\n### Christian-Buddhist Dialogue\\n\\nBuddhism and Christianity have coexisted for four centuries. Scholars have compared Ignatian and Vietnamese Truc Lam Zen traditions and studied Quan Am (Guanyin) and Mary. But most Buddhist-Christian dialogue scholarship comes from other Asian contexts. Vietnam-specific dialogue is its own distinct field.\\n\\n### Christianity and Vietnamese Nationalism\\n\\nThe most politically charged gap. Many Catholics initially supported independence and fought alongside the Viet Minh. Ho Chi Minh attended Christmas Mass in 1945. The full complexity of Christian patriotism, collaboration, resistance, and accommodation has never been synthesized.\\n\\n### Women in Vietnamese Church History\\n\\nOf more than 25,000 religious sisters in Vietnam, very few have held decision-making positions. Yet women comprise the majority of congregations. Among the Hmong, women often convert first, seeing Christianity as a path away from domestic violence.\\n\\n### Digital Church and Social Media Christianity\\n\\nVietnam has one of Southeast Asia's highest internet penetration rates, yet digital Christianity is nearly unstudied.\\n\\n### Persecution Documentation\\n\\nAcademic scholarship contextualizing persecution within Vietnamese legal and political frameworks is limited.","vi":"### Thần học Việt Nam\\n\\nThiên Chúa như Đạo, thờ cúng tổ tiên như khuôn khổ thần học --- những đề xuất đơn lẻ chưa thành truyền thống.\\n\\n### Đối thoại Phật giáo--Kitô giáo\\n\\nBốn thế kỷ chung sống nhưng nghiên cứu đối thoại riêng cho Việt Nam rất ít.\\n\\n### Phụ nữ và giáo hội số\\n\\nPhụ nữ chiếm đa số giáo dân nhưng thiếu tiếng nói; Kitô giáo số gần như chưa được nghiên cứu."}},{"heading":{"en":"Diaspora Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống về cộng đồng hải ngoại"},"content":{"en":"### Viet Kieu Church Dynamics\\n\\nChristians formed approximately 75% of Vietnamese refugees after 1975. The Vietnamese Catholic community in the US numbers around 700,000 faithful, with approximately 1,000 Vietnamese priests. Yet diaspora church scholarship remains thin beyond demographic description.\\n\\n### Second-Generation Faith Retention\\n\\nFirst, second, and third generations hold different relationships to both faith and Vietnamese identity. Empirical data on retention rates and patterns of disaffiliation is scarce.\\n\\n### Vietnamese Christians in Other Asian Countries\\n\\nApproximately 700,000 Vietnamese migrant workers live across Japan, Taiwan, South Korea, and Thailand, many from Catholic backgrounds. Vietnamese migrants are increasingly seen as \\"strategic partners for Church renewal\\" in aging Asian churches --- but this phenomenon has received almost no scholarly attention.\\n\\n### Returnee Faith Patterns\\n\\nWhat happens when diaspora Vietnamese return? Do they bring back transformed religious practices? The returnee faith phenomenon is documented anecdotally but not studied systematically.","vi":"### Động lực giáo hội Việt kiều\\n\\nKhoảng 700.000 người Công giáo Việt tại Mỹ. Nghiên cứu về giáo hội hải ngoại vẫn mỏng.\\n\\n### Giữ đạo thế hệ thứ hai\\n\\nDữ liệu về tỷ lệ giữ đạo rất thiếu.\\n\\n### Người Việt tại các nước châu Á và người hồi hương\\n\\n700.000 lao động Việt tại Nhật, Đài Loan, Hàn Quốc chưa được nghiên cứu. Hiện tượng hồi hương cũng chưa có nghiên cứu hệ thống."}},{"heading":{"en":"Comparative Gaps","vi":"Khoảng trống so sánh"},"content":{"en":"### Vietnam-China Comparison\\n\\nBoth are communist states with growing Christian populations, but trajectories diverge. China's Sinicization campaign has no direct parallel in Vietnam's more pragmatic religious management. In China Christianity grows among the ethnic majority; in Vietnam among minorities.\\n\\n### Vietnam-Philippines Comparison\\n\\nBoth received Catholicism through Iberian colonialism, but the Philippines became over 80% Catholic while Vietnam remained under 10%. A 2024 comparative study found \\"entirely distinct historical pathways.\\"\\n\\n### Vietnam-Korea Comparison\\n\\nBoth experienced war, partition, and foreign intervention, yet South Korea became ~30% Christian while Vietnam remained under 10%. Korea's Christianity began with indigenous intellectuals self-evangelizing; Vietnam's arrived through foreign missionaries. Korea's Protestant boom coincided with industrialization; Vietnam's occurred among marginalized ethnic minorities under communist rule.","vi":"### So sánh Việt Nam--Trung Quốc\\n\\nCả hai là nhà nước cộng sản nhưng quỹ đạo Kitô giáo khác nhau.\\n\\n### So sánh Việt Nam--Philippines\\n\\nPhilippines hơn 80% Công giáo, Việt Nam dưới 10%.\\n\\n### So sánh Việt Nam--Hàn Quốc\\n\\nHàn Quốc ~30% Kitô hữu, Việt Nam dưới 10% --- với những đường đi hoàn toàn khác."}},{"heading":{"en":"Priorities for Future Research","vi":"Ưu tiên cho nghiên cứu tương lai"},"content":{"en":"Three overarching patterns emerge:\\n\\n**The Protestant deficit.** Catholic history is reasonably covered for the colonial period, but Protestant history --- especially explosive post-Doi Moi growth --- has almost no sustained scholarly tradition. The forty-year gap in Protestant historiography (1972--2012) means the most dynamic period of church growth occurred with virtually no academic documentation.\\n\\n**The ethnic minority blind spot.** Ethnic minorities account for three-quarters of Vietnamese evangelicals, yet scholarship remains overwhelmingly focused on Kinh-majority church life. The Hmong conversion phenomenon may be one of the most significant church growth stories of the late twentieth century.\\n\\n**The theology gap.** Vietnam has produced almost no recognized indigenous theology. For a church of nearly 10 million, this represents a significant intellectual deficit with practical consequences for discipleship, leadership formation, and cultural engagement.\\n\\nFor missions organizations and funding bodies, these gaps represent both research opportunities and strategic intelligence needs.","vi":"Ba mô hình chính: Thiếu hụt nghiên cứu Tin Lành, điểm mù về dân tộc thiểu số, và khoảng trống thần học. Với gần 10 triệu Kitô hữu, việc lấp đầy những khoảng trống này là cấp thiết."}}]`),s={id:"03",title:n,summary:i,tags:e,readingTime:t,featured:a,sections:o};export{s as default,a as featured,h as id,t as readingTime,o as sections,i as summary,e as tags,n as title};
